observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct/require the Municipal Accountant to:
(a)	trace and reconcile the monthly variances between the deductions in the payroll including government share as against its corresponding remittances to the Fund in order to facilitate the identification of the persons liable/responsible to said net over remittance, after which, require the concerned employees to refund the amount remitted by the Municipality for the personal shares of their premium contributions and loan amortizations which were not deducted from their respective salaries and if deducted, were less than what was remitted while for other discrepancies noted, prepare the necessary corrective measures or adjustments, as the case maybe; 

(b)	submit to the Audit Team a complete and signed Pag-IBIG Data Entry System Forms as supporting documents to the monthly remittances to the Fund and henceforth, ensure that the total amount to be remitted should be equal to the total amount reflected on said forms, for which the latter should also be equal to the total amount deducted from the salaries of the employees including the LGUs counterpart on premium contributions;

(c)	 submit to the Audit Team the lacking official receipts issued by the Fund to acknowledge the MP2 monthly remittances together with the corresponding signed Pag-IBIG Data Entry System Forms as supporting documents to said monthly remittances, of which no deduction was withheld from the salaries of said employee/s and, upon identification of the concerned employee/s, demand for its refund as such is considered as a members’ savings for which the funds of the Municipality were used to pay and henceforth, ensure that supporting documents are complete before remittance or payment is made; and 

(d)	 maintain subsidiary ledger for each type/nature of deductions withheld from officers and employees including government share for the account of the Pag-IBIG Fund and its corresponding remittances to said Fund in order to ascertain the validity and correctness of the entries posted therein, which generally come from the source documents and, to facilitate its reconciliation to the controlling account in the General Ledger of any variance/s and/or adjustment/s at the end of every month.

We also recommended that management evaluate and strengthen the internal control system on the accounting and cashiering functions/duties and ensure that said functions/duties be segregated not only to prevent or reduce the occurrence of errors or fraud but also to pinpoint accountability and responsibility in safeguarding the LGUs assets.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor: 
(a)	require the Municipal Accountant to prepare the Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF on a monthly basis and the LDRRMO to submit the said report to concerned offices on the required date;


(c)	instruct the MDRRMO to incorporate under a separate caption in the LDRRMFIP the list of projects and activities which are to be charged to the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years which were transferred to the Special Trust Fund.

We recommended and management agreed that LCE require the Municipal Accountant to:
keep and maintain subsidiary records and appropriate Road Network Property Ledger Cards (Annex D of COA Circular No. 2015-08) for ALL roads and road components for every road network;
provide appropriate disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements on Road Network System using the format in Annex B of COA Circular No. 2015-08;
We recommended and management agreed that LCE require the General Services Officer to:
Maintain a complete Road Network Property Cards for ALL roads and road components for every road network;
Maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map.

During the exit conference, the municipal accountant reiterated her need for a permanent employee support staff who will help in the preparation and maintenance of the Property Ledger Cards.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
(a) require the Municipal Accountant to prepare the Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF on a monthly basis and the LDRRMO to submit the said report to concerned offices on the required date;
(b) require the Municipal Budget Officer to comply with the budgetary requirement to set aside not less than five percent (5%) of the estimated revenue from regular sources as the LDRRMF;
(c) instruct the MDRRMO to incorporate under a separate caption in the LDRRMFIP the list of projects and activities which are to be charged to the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years which were transferred to the Special Trust Fund; and
(d) require the Municipal Accountant to facilitate the immediate transfer of the accumulated total unexpended balance of the fund to the Special Trust Fund account to ensure that there is a stand-by fund to be used solely for the purpose of supporting the disaster risk reduction and management activities, as provided in the LDRRMFIP within the next five years. Hereafter, transfer all unexpended/unobligated balance of the QRF and the DRRMF-MOOE to the Special Trust Fund so that any unutilized amount after five years shall be reverted back to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund and shall be made available for other social services after subsequent enactment by the Local Sanggunian.
